On a way to Chebyshev polynomials as basis functions for the tfspline Python module¶

Version 1.0 Date: 2023-03-07 Contact: hannes.waclawek@fh-salzburg.ac.at

In [ ]:
# Imports

import tensorflow as tf

Introduction¶

The Jacobi polynomials
$P_n^{\alpha,\beta}(x)$
are a class of polynomials that are orthogonal with respect to the weight function
$w(x)=(1-x)^\alpha(1+x)^\beta$ on the interval $[-1, 1]$
and the dot product
$\int_{a}^{b} p \cdot q\cdot w(x)\,dx$.
The Gegenbauer polynomials are special cases of the Jacobi polynomials, where
$w(x)=(1-x^2)^{\alpha-\frac{1}{2}}$.
They include the Legendre and Chebyshev polynomials as special cases.
In this notebook, we want to focus on implementing Chebyshev polynomials as a basis for our tfspline module.

(Pre-)Generating Chebyshev polynomials¶

Chebyshev basis functions¶

Let $n \in \mathbb{N_0}$ and $-1 \leq x \leq 1$. The Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind are defined via the recurrence relation
$ T_n(x)= \begin{cases} 1,&\text{if } n = 0\\ x,&\text{if } n = 1\\ 2x\;T_{n-1}(x)-T_{n-2}(x),&\text{else}. \end{cases} $
At the moment, we are only interested in Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, as their roots are famously used as nodes (Chebyshev nodes) in polynomial interpolation to minimize the problem of Runge's phenomenon. We want to verify if these favorable properties for interpolation also generalize to our approximation setting with TensorFlow optimizers. The Chebyshev polynomials $T_0, T_1, \dots, T_n$ form a basis of the vector space of polynomials up to $n$ over $\mathbb{R}$, for all $n \in \mathbb{N_0}$, over the interval $[-1, 1]$. This implies that the $n+1$ Chebyshev polynomials are linearly independent for all $n \in \mathbb{N_0}$.

In [ ]:
spline = model.Spline(polydegree=5, polynum=1, ck=2, basis='chebyshev')
x_arr = np.linspace(-1, 1, 100)

In the tfspline module, we implement the definition above in the _generate_chebyshev_polynomial() function. If we pass the poly1d polynomial/monomial $x$ to that function...

Shifted Chebyshev polynomials¶

The Chebyshev polynomials $T_0, T_1, \dots, T_n$ form a basis of the vector space of polynomials up to $n$ over $\mathbb{R}$, for all $n \in \mathbb{N_0}$, over the interval $[-1, 1]$. Our existing tfspline implementation works in the range $[0,1]$. Generelly, performing analytical and numerical work, it is often more convenient to use the half interval $[0, 1]$ instead of the full interval $[-1, 1]$. Applying an affine transformation, we can change validity of the Chebyshev basis to the range $[0,1]$. This is done by multiplying the shifting function $(2x -1)$ with the Chebyshev polynomial $T_n$
$ T*_n(x) = T_n(2x -1), $
with starting values
$ T*_0(x) = 1\\ T*_1(x) = 2x-1. $
The recurrence relation is adapted to
$ T^*_n(x)= \begin{cases} 1,&\text{if } n = 0\\ 2x-1,&\text{if } n = 1\\ 2(2x-1)\;T^*_{n-1}(x)-T^*_{n-2}(x),&\text{else}. \end{cases} $
The shifted Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind are orthogonal on the support interval [0,1] with respect to the weight function $w(x)=\frac{1}{x-x^2}$ and normalized by the requirement that $T^*_n(1) = 1$. For the first four Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, this leaves us with
$ T^*_0(x) = 1\\ T^*_1(x) = 2x-1\\ T^*_2(x) = 8x^2-8x+1\\ T^*_3(x) = 32x^3-48x^2+18x-1. $

In the tfspline module, we implement the definition above in the _generate_shifted_chebyshev_polynomial() function. If we pass the poly1d polynomial/monomial $x$ to that function...

Chebyshev expansion / series¶

Let $a_i \in \mathbb{R}$. Then the Chebyshev expansion / Chebyshev series
$ \sum_{i=0}^{n}a_i\;T_i(x) $
evaluates to a polynomial of degree $n$.
Example:
Let $a_i = (1, 2, 3)$, then
$ p(x) = 1 \cdot 1 + 2 \cdot x + 3 \cdot (2x \cdot x - 1) \\ = 6x^2 + 2x - 2. $

In [ ]:

spline.initialize_l2fit = False

Attention¶

Shifting polynomial centers to the mean of the interval does affect the result here, while it does not for "vanilla" Chebyshev, since the center of the interval is no longer 0.

Derivatives of Chebyshev series¶

Using the monomial $x$ in poly1d form, with our _evaluate_chebyshev() function, we can generate all needed Chebyshev polynomials and store them for later use We can now extend this principle to pre-generate derivatives for all non-zero (according to degree parameter) derivatives. The highest possible derivative number, for which the function will not be 0, is $n$. e.g. $f(x) = 16 x^5 -20x^3+5x, n=5$ $f^{(5)}(x) = 16 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1$ We create derivatives for polynomials with monomial base by modifying coefficients like $[a, b, c, d, …]$ to $[b, 2c, 3d, …]$.

We now have a Chebyshev Series in the form $f(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_i \cdot T_i(x),$ where $a_i$ are the TensorFlow variables to optimize.

Since we now have all relevant Chebyshev polynomial derivatives $T_i^{(d)}$, we can formulate the derivative as $f^{(d)}(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_i \cdot T_i^{(d)}(x).$

This allows us to pre-generate relevant Chebyshev derivatives in the beginning of the training loop and re-use them.

Generate input data and rescale axes¶

The input space needs to be rescaled such that every polynomial segment is in the range [0, 1]. This allows for same optimization conditions for all segments. See paper for details.

In [ ]:
[data_x, data_y] = sampledata.generate_sample_data_sin(n=100, f=1, noise_factor=0)
data_x = sampledata.rescale_input_data(data_x, n_segments)

Discussion¶

The best results are achieved with shifted Chebyshev polynomials as a basis. shift_polynomial_centers='boundary' is very important, as fitting does not converge without shifting.

Discussion¶

With degree 5 polynomials and C^2^ continuity, Power Basis shows the best result in the combined L2 + C^k^-error setting. Interestingly, shifted Chebyshev polynomials produce an unfavourable result although optimization without C^k^ - optimization already produces an almost C^2^ - continuous result.

Test Spline from coeffs function¶

This functionality is required to create splines from coeffs returned by model.parallel() experiments, as the tf.Spline class is not picklable and cannot be returned by parallel tasks under Windows. See https://docs.python.org/2/library/multiprocessing.html#windows .

Things that do not work with new basis¶

Strictly establishing continuity via algorithm¶

Old approach doesn't directly apply to new setting - We use Power Basis coefficients in the algorithm which don't go along with Chebyshev series coefficients.
